`crates/` is the workspace root: five independent binaries (ctx-cage,
ctx-context, ctx-scan, ctx-summarize, ctx-verify) plus one shared library
crate (ctx-core). Depending on this workspace gets you a full ctx toolchain
— sandboxed execution, context-chain resolution/serving, filesystem
scanning for staleness, LLM-driven summarization, and check verification —
each usable standalone as a binary or, for ctx-core, as a linked dependency.

The only code-level coupling across crates is ctx-core: both ctx-scan and
ctx-context depend on it for path-safety checks and the hash-sidecar
schema, so a change to that schema or to path-safety semantics must be
validated against both downstream crates, not just ctx-core's own tests.
Beyond that, the crates are decoupled at the source level but share a
format-level contract implicitly: ctx-context reads exactly the
`rollup.ctx`/`.ctx` files that ctx-summarize writes, and both independently
assume the same `.context` mirror-path layout and the `--- label ---`
rollup-input convention — a layout change in one requires a matching
change in the other even though neither imports the other's code.

Each crate's own rollup is authoritative for its internals; nothing here
restates them. No workspace-level `intent.md` exists, so no divergence can
be assessed.